            [
              'id' => '4',
              'user_id' => '3',
              'post_type_id' => '1',
              'title' => 'China deal and cotton',
              'descr' => '<p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">On the day when the United States-China trade deal (Phase 1) was signed in Washington, DC, cotton growers gathered for the Plains Cotton Growers&rsquo; Board meeting recently, to talk about 2019 crop, trade situation and the cotton market.</p>
              <a href="https://www.textiletoday.com.bd/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/USA-China-trade-deal-Phase-1-Cotton.jpg" style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.3s ease 0s; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(63, 81, 181);"><img src="https://www.textiletoday.com.bd/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/USA-China-trade-deal-Phase-1-Cotton.jpg" alt="USA-China trade deal (Phase-1) & Cotton" width="640" height="359" style="box-sizing: inherit; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; background: transparent; height: auto; max-width: 100%;" class="fr-fil fr-dib"></a>

            <p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">Reece Langley, Vice President of Operations at Memphis-based National Cotton Council presented information about the trade situation. This scribe had an opportunity to talk with Langley on the sidelines of the meeting about the trade deal signed and its impact on the United States&rsquo; cotton sector.</p>

            <p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">With the signing of the deal, China&rsquo;s import of the United States&rsquo; agricultural products would reach at least US$ 40 billion per year. Potential is there for US$ 50 billion/year. Langley stated that commodity wise itemization is not known yet. United States&rsquo; cotton sales to China during the 2017 calendar year was 2.5 million bales (480 lbs. each) worth about US$ 1 billion. The sales of agricultural products in that year to China was about US$ 24 billion. The trade deal is expected to enhance this value by US$ 16 billion.</p>

            <p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">Langley hoped that the U.S. cotton&rsquo;s market share in China would at least reach the pre-tariff era. The tariff regime has brought down the share to about 18% last year.</p>

            <p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">Producing and delivering high quality and clean cotton will help to regain the market share. Dahlen Hancock, Lynn county farmer in the High Plains for 39 years stated, &ldquo;we have to keep striving to provide superior quality as the world needs quality cotton.&rdquo;</p>

            <p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">Regional and international trade pacts such as the United States-Mexico-Canada Agreement (USMCA), which is expected to be passed by the U.S. Senate this week, provides certainty for the existing marketing condition, stated Langley.</p>

            <p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">&ldquo;The recently signed Phase 1of the China trade agreement has the potential to provide resumption of access to an important market for Texas cotton producers.&nbsp;Confirmation of that will be actual sales to China, and we hope that comes to fruition soon,&rdquo; stated Steve Verett, Chief Executive Officer of Lubbock-based Plains Cotton Growers, Inc.</p>

            <p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">The mechanism by which China is going to enable this trade deal to fruition will be interesting watch&mdash;maybe by providing tariff exemption to imports to achieve the target.</p>',
              'status' => '10',
              'is_article' => '1'
            ],

            [
              'id' => '5',
              'user_id' => '3',
              'post_type_id' => '1',
              'title' => 'Digital textile printing ink market to reach US$2.1 bn by 2023',
              'descr' => '<p style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px 0px 17px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: rgb(255, 255, 255); color: rgb(102, 102, 102); font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; font-size: 17px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial;">With the evolution of industry 4.0, the digital textile printing ink technology is constantly crossing new boundaries. According to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.alliedmarketresearch.com/digital-textile-printing-inks-market" rel="noopener" style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.3s ease 0s; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(63, 81, 181);" target="_blank">alliedmarketresearch</a> global<strong style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: transparent; font-weight: 700;">&nbsp;</strong><a href="https://www.alliedmarketresearch.com/press-release/digital-textile-printing-inks-market.html" rel="noopener" style="box-sizing: inherit; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; background-color: transparent; transition: all 0.3s ease 0s; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; color: rgb(63, 81, 181);" target="_blank">digital textile printing inks market</a> was valued at US$698 million in 2016, and is expected to reach US$2.1 billion by 2023, registering a CAGR of 17.2% from 2017 to 2023.</p>

